            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;It&apos;s not the fact that &lt;code&gt;void*&lt;/code&gt; can point to anything that enables this; it&apos;s the fact that a &lt;code&gt;void*&lt;/code&gt; can be &lt;i&gt;implicitly converted&lt;/i&gt; to any other pointer type. To clarify the distinction, in C++ a &lt;code&gt;void*&lt;/code&gt; can still point to anything, but implicit conversion was removed, so one must cast.&lt;/span&gt;

              &lt;div class=&quot;d-inline-flex ai-center&quot;&gt;
